08651nam a22011535i 9783110515695DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20172017gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105156957 a10.1515/97831105156952doi  a(DE-B1597)472643  a(OCoLC)984656933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh0481pa930qDE-10100aPanhellenes at Methone :bGraphê in Late Geometric and Protoarchaic Methone, Macedonia (ca 700 BCE) /ced. by Jenny Strauss Clay, Irad Malkin, Yannis Z. Tzifopoulos. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (X, 377 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v4400tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Graphê and Archaeology -- tTransport Amphorae from Methone: An Interdisciplinary Study of Production and Trade ca. 700 BCE -- tThe Archaeological Background of the Earliest Graffiti and Finds from Methone -- tTo Write and to Paint: More Early Iron Age Potters′ Marks in the Aegean -- tCounting on Pots? Reflections on Numerical Notations in Early Iron Age Greece -- tTexts and Amphoras in the Methone “Ypogeio” -- tPart II: Graphê, Alphabet, Dialect, and Language -- tFrom Gabii and Gordion to Eretria and Methone: the Rise of the Greek Alphabet -- tAlphabets and Dialects in the Euboean Colonies of Sicily and Magna Graecia or What Could Have Happened in Methone -- tAlphabet and Phonology at Methone: Beginning a Typology of Methone Alphabetic Symbols and an Alternative Hypothesis for Reading Hακεσάνδρō -- tThoughts on the Initial Aspiration of HAKEΣANΔPO -- tThe Impact of Late Geometric Greek Inscriptions from Methone on Understanding the Development of Early Euboean Alphabet -- tMethone of Pieria: a Reassessment of Epigraphical Evidence (with a Special Attention to Pleonastic Sigma) -- tPart III: Graphê and Culture -- tLocal ‘Literacies’ in the Making: Early Alphabetic Writing and Modern Literacy Theories -- tForm Follows Function? Toward an Aesthetics of Early Greek Inscriptions at Methone -- tWine and the Early History of the Greek Alphabet -- tBibliography and Abbreviations -- tNotes on Contributors -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume discusses the multidimensional aspects of the unique, and so far unprecedented for Macedonia, 191 sherds from Methone in Pieria, dated to ca 700 BCE, which bear inscriptions, graffiti, and (trade)marks inscribed, incised, scratched and rarely painted. The 191 vessels were unearthed during excavations in ancient Methone in Pieria, the oldest colony of Greeks from Eretria in the north according to tradition. The Methone find is unique for two reasons. First, most of the pottery dates between 730 and 700 BCE, a period from which very few examples of Greek writing survives. And second, inscribed ceramics, scratched or painted, are extremely rare in Macedonia. This new evidence of inscribed pottery from Methone is invaluable for classical studies, and the papers of this volume contribute notably to current discussions about: the Greeks and the Greek language in Macedonia; the Greek colonization; the pottery trade and the early Greek transport amphoras; trade, the symposium, and other contexts for the development of writing; the ‘alphabets’ of Methone and the introduction of the alphabet in Greece; the dialect(s) of Methone in relation to the Greek dialects; early Greek writing, literacy, and literary beginnings.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aInscriptions, GreekxMacedoniaxEuropexMacedonia. 0aInscriptions, GreekzMacedonia. 4aGriechische Inschrift. 4aGriechisches Alphabet. 4aHandel. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGreek alphabet.  aGreek inscriptions.  atrade.1 aBessios, Matthaios, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharalambidou, Xenia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClay, Jenny Strauss, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDell’Oro, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDosuna, Julián Méndez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanko, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiriatzi, Evangelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKotsonas, Antonis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKourou, Nota, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkin, Irad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalkin, Irad, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMüller, Noémi Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOikonomaki, Niki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanayotou-Triantaphyllopoulou, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapadopoulos, John K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPappas, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoumpou, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkelton, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrauss Clay, Jenny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTzifopoulos, Yannis Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTzifopoulos, Yannis Z.